<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="179" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d179">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                                        (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-06">January 6,
                                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p rend="flushleft"><hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the
                                        President</hi>:</p>
                                <p>The attached is a telegram which Churchill proposes to send to
                                    the Dutch apropos of their complaints about the agreement.<note n="1" xml:id="d179fn1">The attached telegram was a copy of
                                        Churchill’s draft telegram of January 5, 1942, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_305">p.
                                            305</ref>.</note></p>
                                <p>I gave it to Stark and he consulted Marshall, King and Arnold and
                                    they find the telegram is all right.</p>
                                <p>Immediately following the draft telegram is a memorandum of
                                    explanation which Stark drafted.<note n="2" xml:id="d179fn2">The
                                        attachment was a copy of Stark’s letter to Hopkins, <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                                    </note> I don’t quite understand it but the main thing is that
                                    your staff recommend that the cable go as dictated.</p>
                                <p>If it has your approval I will give it to the British and they
                                    will get it off tonight.<note n="3" xml:id="d179fn3">The
                                        memorandum was returned with the handwritten notation:
                                        “H.L.H.—OK FDR”.</note></p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harry L. Hopkins</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>